1. Nf3 { The Reti is a popular opening at all levels, particularly in shorter formats of the game. White can play the first few moves by hand irrespective of what Black plays. This simplifies opening theory for White but it allows Black to equalise much easier compared to either d4 or e4. White can transpose anytime with the move d4 but there is no real benefit in this move order. } ( 1. b3 { The dreaded 1.b3 :) I think it is more of a meme online these days than people taking it seriously. There are multiple good systems to go for but we will keep our play similar to the lines we have seen so far. } 1... d5 2. Bb2 Bf5 { We get the bishop out of the pawn chain before we go for the move e6. However, unlike the lines we have seen so far we can get the bishop directly to f5. White has played very slowly with the move b3 and is not in a position to exploit our queenside. The lines with Qb3 are usually the critical ones. } ) ( 1. f4 { The Bird is a pretty aggressive but also dubious first move. Moving the 'f' pawn comes with the risk of weakening the king. } 1... d5 { Our play will be pretty similar to the lines we have seen so far. There are some cases though where we go for the move ...g6. } ) 1... d5 { We immediately take control of the centre. This is part of our standard setup against every move other than 1.e4. } 2. g3 Bg4 { We get the bishop out before going for the move e6. Typically the concern for us in these lines is that the bishop is passive on c8. Here, we get the bishop out of the pawn chain immediately. The drawback is that the queenside and the b7 pawn in particular are exposed but it is not easy to exploit them. I have played this for over 7 years with good results. } 3. Bg2 { There are a few different move orders here. You need to understand exactly why we play every move. } ( 3. Ne5 { We will see all the Ne5 jumps in the first chapter without including the move h3. This is a pretty early one as White tries to exploit our previous move. } ) 3... c6 4. O-O ( 4. c4 { In the 2nd chapter, we will see all the lines including an early c4. White has a few concrete ideas before we finish our development. } 4... e6 { We do not yet commit the knights as we are waiting to see how White reacts here. If he continues slowly then we will develop them to d7 and f6 but we keep the options open for now. } ) 4... Nd7 { There are other move orders possible but we cannot avoid the move ... Nd7 forever. We might as well play it immediately as we have the option to go . ..e5 in the centre quickly. Another benefit is that we stop the move c4 right now. } 5. h3 { This is the more critical move here, forcing us to make the choice very early. White can then play according to the choice we make. } ( 5. d3 Ngf6 { White has the dilemma of whether to or not to include the moves h3 and .. .Bh5. There are two ways to prepare for the move e4- Nbd2 or Qe1. We will see the Qe1 plan in the 4th chapter and the more common Nbd2 in the next. } 6. Nbd2 ( 6. c4 { We are going to see the same c4 plan but in a more clever way. White waits for us to commit our knight to d7. He then goes c4 and will take on d5 next as we cannot get our knight to c6 anymore. Along with the d4 systems, this is the most critical option for White to fight for an advantage. } ) 6... e5 { Against these slow systems, we will try to take control of the centre very quickly. We will not take on e4 early and keep maintaining the tension for as long as possible. } ) ( 5. d4 { We are going to see these d4 structures in the 6th and 7th chapters. There is a big difference in the move order though. It is more critical with the inclusion of the moves h3 and ...Bh5. The key difference is that now we are able to retreat to f5 in many cases. } ) 5... Bh5 { This is the best option away from ideas of Nh4 but this means that we are not able to bring the bishop back to e6 or f5. } 6. d4 { This will be the most critical chapter as White tries to create play in the centre before we castle. He will try to stop us from castling kingside. } *

