1. Nf3 { The Reti is a popular opening at all levels, particularly in shorter formats of the game. White can play the first few moves by hand irrespective of what Black plays. This simplifies opening theory for White but it allows Black to equalise much easier compared to either d4 or e4. White can transpose anytime with the move d4 but there is no real benefit in this move order. } 1... d5 { We immediately take control of the centre. This is part of our standard setup against every move other than 1.e4. } 2. g3 Bg4 { We get the bishop out before going for the move e6. Typically the concern for us in these lines is that the bishop is passive on c8. Here, we get the bishop out of the pawn chain immediately. The drawback is that the queenside and the b7 pawn in particular are exposed but it is not easy to exploit them. I have played this for over 7 years with good results. } ( 2... Bf5 { This is another line I considered but White has some concrete ways to pose problems for us. There are some situations where we are able to take on f3 in our system which is not possible here. } ) 3. Bg2 { This is the usual plan here and we will see this in the next few chapters. There are a few different move orders here. You need to understand exactly why we play every move. } ( 3. Ne5 { We will see all the Ne5 jumps in this chapter without including the move h3. This is a pretty early one as White tries to exploit our previous move. } 3... Bf5 4. c4 { This has been played by a few strong players but Black has an easy way to equalise here. } ( 4. Bg2 { will likely transpose to the main line but we we can try to take over the position after } 4... f6 5. Nf3 e5 6. c4 d4 { We have an amazing pawn structure in the centre. White has to do something dynamic as otherwise we are doing extremely well. } 7. Nh4 ( 7. O-O Nc6 8. d3 a5 $11 { We stop all counterplay for White and we can develop our kingside slowly. White is far from opening up the 'e' file. } ) 7... Bc8 8. e3 Ne7 $11 { [%cal Gb8c6] We will castle queenside here with ...Nc6, ...Be6 and ...Qd7 next. } ) 4... f6 $1 { We need to be willing to play such lines to take control over the centre. } ( 4... c6 { This was the start of a nightmare for Black in a recent rapid game online. } 5. Qb3 Qb6 6. cxd5 Qxb3 7. axb3 Be4 { Black felt that he had equalised here but he got a cold shower after } 8. dxc6 Bxh1 9. Rxa7 $1 { Black resigned in the game 1-0 (9) Caruana, F (2796) -Firouzja, A (2744) Chess.com INT 2024. } ) 5. Nf3 dxc4 { We want White to waste a couple of moves to win the pawn back. } ( 5... d4 { is also possible. } ) 6. Bg2 ( 6. Na3 e5 7. Nxc4 Be6 8. b3 Nc6 9. Bb2 Qd7 { We are ready to castle queenside next. Our king will be safe on b8. We will go ...Bh3 and trade the light-squared bishops. We are faster to create an attack on the kingside. } 10. Bg2 O-O-O $36 ) 6... Nc6 7. b3 { White is hoping to create quick play on the queenside. He wants to open up some files. } ( 7. O-O e5 8. b3 Qd7 $36 { As we saw earlier, we will castle queenside and start attacking on the kingside with the move ...Bh3. } ) 7... e5 { We are not concerned about the material here. We will allow White to take on c4 and keep the 'c' file closed. The value of tempo is high in these positions and White has wasted two moves to recapture the pawn. } 8. bxc4 Qd7 9. O-O Bh3 $36 { We trade the bishop immediately. As White has committed his king early to the kingside, we will quickly go ...h5-h4 next. We can castle anytime. } ) 3... c6 { This is the most necessary move in all the different systems here and is pretty flexible. We are looking to bring our knight on d7 next. } ( 3... Nf6 { This is not a great move order in my opinion as White gets an extra option now. } 4. c4 c6 5. Ne5 $14 { This plan is not effective in our move order but here it makes a huge difference/ } ) ( 3... Nd7 { I have played this a few times earlier but I feel it is not very flexible. We are committing the knight to d7 when it could have gone directly to c6 in some lines. } ) 4. Ne5 { White gets his knight to e5 before we delay it with the move ...Nd7. } 4... Bf5 { In general, we meet the move h3 with ...Bh5 and Ne5 with ...Bf5. This is because, with the pawn on h3, White could go after the bishop on f5 with Nh4. And with the knight on e5, the move g4 is an option for White. } 5. d4 ( 5. c4 e6 6. O-O ( 6. cxd5 exd5 7. O-O Nd7 8. d4 Ngf6 { transposes. } ) 6... Nd7 { We want to trade the strong knight on e5 as soon as possible. In such situations, if we are careless, White can suddenly take over with moves like g4 at some point. } 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. d3 ( 8. cxd5 { only helps us as after } 8... exd5 $36 { we can start attacking on the kingside with . ..h5 next. The bishop can now go to h3 to eliminate a key defender. } ) 8... dxc4 { is the simplest approach here. } ( 8... d4 $5 { I like this move, keeping the queens on the board. Next, we can go ...e5 followed by an attack on the kingside. } 9. Nd2 e5 $40 { [%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] } ) 9. dxc4 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 e5 $11 { We get a comfortable endgame with the pawn on e5. The bishop on g2 is restricted by our c6 pawn. } ) 5... Nd7 6. O-O ( 6. Nd3 { Has been played in a few games but it is not a great square for the knight. } 6... e6 7. O-O h5 $5 { With the knight on d3, it is very tempting to start an attack on the kingside. } 8. Nd2 Ngf6 $36 { We ensure that White is not able to go e4 in the centre. We are ready to go ...h4 next. } ) 6... e6 7. c4 Ngf6 8. Nc3 ( 8. cxd5 { We have seen this earlier. Our decision is easier now as the knight has already landed on d7. } 8... exd5 9. Nc3 Be7 { We are happy to continue slowly here. The bishop on g2 is well restricted by the pawns in the centre. } 10. h3 ( 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. Qxb6 axb6 $11 { We have managed to improve our pawn structure with ...b5-b4 coming up next. } ) ( 10. Bf4 O-O 11. h3 h6 $11 { We create a square on h7 for the bishop. We are doing very well positionally and White is the one struggling with his light-squared bishop. } ) 10... h6 11. g4 Bh7 12. f4 { White wants to create something on the kingside. } 12... O-O 13. Be3 Ne4 { We will either trade on c3 or bring the knight to d6 next. We can then go for the move ...f6 and kick the knight out. } 14. f5 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Re8 { With the pawn on f5, it is easier to force the knight away from e5. } 16. Bf4 Bg5 $11 { If the bishop moves back, we can go ...f6 and get the bishop to e3. } ) 8... Be7 { We are planning to take on e5 next followed by ...Nd7. White has to find some ways to deal with it. } 9. Qb3 ( 9. h3 h6 { We anticipate the move g4 and create a luft for our bishop. } 10. Qb3 Qb6 { We are happy to trade the queens. One of the threats now is to take on b3 and go ...Bc2, winning the b3 pawn. } 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Rd8 $11 { We will take on b3 next and put our pawn on a6. The queenside is secure and we will slowly start to play against the d4 pawn. } ) ( 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Rc1 { This was tried by Fabi but it was a bullet game. } ( 10. Re1 h6 { We are waiting for White to go for the move e4. It will only give us more targets in the centre. } 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bxe4 g5 $36 { We want to take on e5 and e4 in the next two moves. We will get a same coloured bishop endgame with a target on e5. } ) 10... h6 11. h3 Bh7 { We wait to see how White is going to continue. I do not see a good plan for him. } 12. a3 Nb6 { We force White to release the tension with the 'c' pawn. } ( 12... g5 { is another typical idea in these positions. } 13. Bd2 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 $11 ) 13. c5 Nbd7 $11 { We are threatening to go ...g5 next. } ) 9... Qb6 10. Nxd7 { There was no other option as we were planning to take on e5 the next move. } 10... Nxd7 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Rd8 { The rook is well placed on d8, keeping an eye on d4. We will likely take on b3 next move. The endgame is equal with White's space advantage compensating for the weak d4 pawn. } 13. Be3 ( 13. Rd1 Qxb3 14. axb3 a6 $11 ) 13... Qxb3 14. axb3 a6 $11 { [%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] There is not much play for White in these positions. If he removes the knight from e4, we can get our bishop to c2. We can consider going ...h5-h4 next, to soften up the kingside. } *

