1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 ( 3... Nf6 4. c4 { is much more dangerous for Black. } ) 4. c4 { In this chapter, we will see all the lines including an early c4. White has a few concrete ideas before we finish our development. } 4... e6 { We do not yet commit the knights as we are waiting to see how White reacts here. If he continues slowly then we will develop them to d7 and f6 but we keep the options open for now. } 5. cxd5 { This is a critical try here to clarify the pawn structure in the centre. The play differs a lot depending on how we recapture the pawn. } ( 5. O-O Nf6 { This will be examined in the next chapter. } ) ( 5. Qb3 Qb6 { We have no issues with d5 firmly under control. } 6. d3 { White does not want to completely block the centre. } ( 6. d4 Nd7 7. Nc3 Ngf6 8. O-O Be7 $11 { We will see this position in upcoming chapters. This is one of the typical positions in this line and we are pretty comfortable. } ) 6... Nd7 7. O-O ( 7. Be3 Qxb3 8. axb3 Bb4+ { The bishop is very well placed here, clamping White's queenside. } 9. Bd2 { White has to waste a tempo to trade the bishops. } 9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 Ngf6 $11 { We reach an equal endgame. I like our chances as will be able to keep the king in the centre. } ) 7... Qxb3 8. axb3 Bxf3 $5 { This is an unusual move, giving up the bishop voluntarily. But we want to go after the b3 pawn with ...Nc5 next. The knight on f3 could have then jumped to e5 with a tempo. } 9. Bxf3 Bb4 { [%cal Gd7c5] It is not easy for White to defend the b3 pawn with the bishop on b4, controlling the d2 square. } 10. Ra2 $5 { This is clever as White moves the rook away in anticipation of ... Nc5-b3. } 10... f5 $1 { We have multiple good plans in the position. We want to control the light squares in the position. We will put our knight on f6 next with great control over e4. } ( 10... Nc5 { is also possible and the line continues } 11. Bd2 $1 Bxd2 12. Nxd2 Nf6 $11 ) 11. Na3 Ngf6 12. Nc2 Bd6 $11 ) 5... Bxf3 $1 { We give up the bishop voluntarily to be able to recapture with the 'c' pawn. We really want to get the knight to c6 and White's light-squared bishop is restricted by our d5 pawn. This is an important point here and I have had pretty good results in the few games I played here. } ( 5... cxd5 { is a huge blunder due to } 6. Qa4+ $18 ) ( 5... exd5 { This is a common recapture but I am not a fan of this structure as White can go e4 soon and open up the centre. Our knight would be much better on c6, compared to d7. } 6. O-O Nf6 7. h3 Bh5 8. d3 Nbd7 9. Nc3 Bc5 10. Qb3 { This is another annoying move as we are unable to defend the b7 pawn easily. } 10... Bb6 11. Na4 { I faced this in one of my earliest games in this line- 1/2-1/2 (51) Korpa, B (2513) -Arjun, K (2370) Benasque 2018. It is an unpleasant position for Black as he loses the bishop pair. } ) 6. Bxf3 cxd5 { The first question for White is whether he goes for the move d4 or keeps the pawn on d3. We are very consistent in our approach against both these moves. } 7. O-O Nc6 8. d4 { White gets better control over the centre now but he will not be able to open up the position. } ( 8. d3 { This looks logical to keep more flexibility in White's position. However, we get very good control over the centre and it is very hard to get the e4 break. The dark squares in White's position are a big issue for him. } 8... Nf6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Bg2 ( 10. e4 { This is a very tempting move for White to try and open up the position. } 10... d4 $1 { We gain space in the centre and keep it blocked. } ( 10... dxe4 { I went for this in one of my online rapid games 1/2-1/2 (80) Enkhnar, E (2368) -Arjun, K (2477) Chess.com INT 2020. It was better to fully close the centre. } ) 11. Nb1 ( 11. Ne2 O-O 12. Bg2 Nd7 { The knight is headed to the queenside to target the d3 pawn. } 13. f4 Qb6 14. Rb1 Nc5 $15 { We will continue with ... a5-a4 on the queenside. I do not see any good plan for White. } ) 11... Nd7 { The knight is heading to c5. White cannot do much on the kingside while we have much easier play on the other side of the board. } 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Bg2 a5 { We want to gain as much space as possible on the queenside. } 14. f4 Nb4 15. Nf3 Nc5 16. Ne1 a4 $11 { [%cal Gd8b6,Gb6b5,Gf8c8,Ga8a6] We will bring our queen to b5 next to target the d3 pawn. One of our rooks will come to the 'c' file while the other rook can get into the game via a6. } ) ( 10. Bd2 O-O 11. a3 Rc8 { All of these moves are necessary moves, improving our position. We go for these against most of White's options. } 12. b4 h5 $5 { This is a very useful move in these positions to go ...h4 next. We will keep the pawn on h4, creating some unpleasant pressure on the kingside. We make use of the fact that we have traded the knight on f3. } 13. Bg2 h4 $11 ) 10... O-O 11. a3 Rc8 12. Bd2 h5 $5 { Once again we see the same idea to go ...h4 on the kingside. This was played in only one OTB game and it was one of my best wins here. } 13. h3 { This is more prudent, planning to meet ...h4 with g4. } ( 13. e4 { This was a serious error but it is a very human move. White wants to do something concrete. } 13... dxe4 14. dxe4 Qb6 15. b4 Rfd8 $17 { Now. all our pieces are into the game and White faces a lot of issues along the 'd' file. The d4 square is a big weakness and I went on to win in the game 0-1 (36) Gomes, M (2354) -Arjun, K (2537) Cattolica 2021. } ) 13... Qd7 14. Rc1 Rfd8 $11 { We just continue developing normally. We can put our pawn on g6 next and eventually bring our bishop to the a1-h8 diagonal. } ) ( 8. Nc3 Nf6 ( 8... f5 $2 9. d3 $16 { White will get the e4 break next. } ) 9. d4 ) 8... Nf6 ( 8... f5 $5 { This is a very interesting option in this move order. However, I am not analysing it deeply as White has several other move orders to avoid it completely. } 9. Nc3 Bd6 10. e3 Nf6 11. Bd2 g5 $5 ( 11... O-O { is simpler preparing to go ...g5 next. } ) 12. e4 fxe4 13. Bh5+ Nxh5 14. Qxh5+ Kd7 15. Bxg5 ( 15. f3 $13 ) 15... Qe8 16. Qh3 Qg6 17. Be3 Ne7 $15 { 0-1 (33) Kozganbay,E (2337) -Aditya,M (2563) Astana 2023 } ) 9. Nc3 { transposes. } 9... Be7 10. e3 ( 10. b3 { White delays playing the move a3 but he cannot do it indefinitely. } 10... O-O 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. Rc1 Qa5 { We want to go ... Ba3 next to trade the dark-squared bishops. Playing against the bishop pair, it is a good idea to trade one of them. Moreover, there are a lot of weaknesses on the queenside to exploit. } 13. a3 Qb6 14. Na4 Qb5 $11 { White has to repeat as otherwise we will go after b3 with ...Na5. } ) 10... O-O 11. Bd2 ( 11. Qe2 Rc8 ( 11... Na5 { This is a standard plan but it does not work as well with the bishop still on c1. } 12. Rd1 Nc4 $6 13. e4 $14 ) 12. Bd2 g6 { We are going to go ...h5 next, gaining space on the kingside. This is a secure pawn structure for us. } 13. Rfd1 h5 14. Rac1 Re8 { We will put the bishop on f8. Then, we can go ...Re7-c7, fighting for the 'c' file. } 15. Be1 Bf8 $11 { [%cal Ge8e7,Ge7c7] } ) 11... Na5 $5 { Now, it is a different story and we want to get the knight to c4 quickly to win the dark-squared bishop. White is not in time to tuck the bishop on e1. } 12. b3 { Already, provoking the move b3 is an achievement for us. It weakens the dark squares in White's queenside. } ( 12. Qe2 Nc4 13. Rfc1 Nxd2 { If we get a chance, we should eliminate the bishop. } 14. Qxd2 Qd7 $11 { We reach an even middlegame/endgame. The rooks are likely to be traded off on the 'c' file. } ) 12... Rc8 13. Qe2 Re8 $14 { We saw this move earlier. We will put the bishop on f8 and go ...g6 and ...h5 on the kingside. Another plan is to double the rooks on the 'c' file with ...Re7-c7 instead of moving the queen. } 14. Bg2 ( 14. Rfc1 Ba3 15. Rc2 Nc6 $11 ) 14... h5 15. h4 g6 16. Rfc1 Ba3 $5 { We want to misplace the rook on c1. } ( 16... Nc6 { is simpler } 17. a3 Bf8 $11 { [%cal Ge8e7,Ge7c7] } ) 17. Nxd5 $1 { This is the best here, giving up the exchange. } ( 17. Rc2 Nc6 $11 ) 17... Bxc1 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. Bxc1 Nc6 $11 { We get a complex fighting position with chances for both sides which is exactly what we want. We have to be careful along the dark squares here and try to trade as many pieces as possible. } *

