1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O { We are going to see the same c4 plan but in a more clever way. White waits for us to commit our knight to d7. He will then go c4 and take on d5 as we cannot get our knight to c6 anymore. Along with the d4 systems, this is the most critical option for White to fight for an advantage. } 4... Nd7 { There are other move orders possible but we cannot avoid the move ...Nd7 forever. We might as well play it immediately as we have the option to go ...e5 in the centre quickly. Another benefit is that we stop the move c4 right now. } 5. d3 ( 5. c4 { runs into } 5... Bxf3 $1 { We give up the bishop but White faces a lot of issues with the c4 pawn. } 6. Bxf3 ( 6. exf3 dxc4 7. f4 Ngf6 $11 { White is not going to be able to win c4 easily and the 'd' pawn will be isolated. } ) 6... Ne5 { We either win the c4 pawn or the bishop on f3. Both of them are an issue for White. } 7. c5 Nxf3+ 8. exf3 e6 $11 { We get a very comfortable position, having eliminated White's bishop and weakened his pawn structure. } ) 5... Ngf6 { If White continues to play slowly, we are ready to go for the move ...e5 next. } ( 5... e5 { is too early } 6. c4 $14 ) 6. h3 { This is more popular to force the bishop to h5 early. } ( 6. c4 { This is the main subject of this chapter, with or without the inclusion of the move h3. Both of them often transpose into one another. It is one of the most critical tries against our system. } 6... dxc4 $1 { I prepared this way back in 2019. I remember vividly that we had a camp with former WCH Vladimir Kramnik on the Reti in 2020 (from the White side) . At that point, this was not very popular and he was pretty impressed about this idea. } ( 6... e6 { This is the main move by far but I am not a fan of all of these structures. White will take on d5 and quickly go for the move e4. } 7. cxd5 exd5 ( 7... cxd5 { does not make much sense with the knight on d7. } 8. Qb3 $14 ) 8. h3 Bh5 9. e4 $14 ) 7. dxc4 e6 { This is once again pretty rare. Most games have continued with the move e5 which looks more active but it creates some weaknesses. } 8. Nc3 ( 8. b3 { This is too slow to pose any problems for us. } 8... Be7 9. Bb2 h6 $11 { We will now retreat to f5 with the bishop and we have the h7 square. } ) ( 8. Bf4 { This is usually the best square for the bishop to stop us from going ...Qc7. } 8... h6 { This is a new plan which has not been played much. There are no games in this position. We hint at going for the move ...g5 on the kingside. This is particularly relevant when White has played the move h3 on the kingside. } 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Qc2 Nh5 { We kick the bishop away from f4 to get the queen to c7. } 11. Bd2 { White does not block the e2 pawn and he can bring the rook to d1 next. } ( 11. Be3 { allows us to go } 11... Bf5 $11 ) 11... O-O 12. h3 Bf5 13. e4 Bh7 $11 { We will go ...Qc7 next and bring the rook to d8. Once the queen is on c7, we can bring the knight back to f6 as we can meet Bf4 with ...e5. } ) 8... h6 $1 { We saw this plan in the previous move here it has been played twice by Keymar, V. The reason why we do this before ...Be7 is that we now have the option to get the bishop to d6 if the queen goes to c2. } 9. Qc2 ( 9. b3 Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Nh4 { White is trying to win our light-squared bishop. } 11... Qc7 { We stop White from going h3 and g4. } 12. h3 Bh5 13. g4 Bxg4 $1 14. hxg4 Nxg4 { We attack the knight and threaten mate on h2. He can stop both the threats but we have enough resources to continue attacking. } 15. Nf3 Nde5 $15 ) 9... Bd6 $5 { This is an extra option we get due to White's move order. } ( 9... Be7 { will likely transpose to other lines. } ) 10. Rd1 ( 10. b3 Bf5 { We immediately provoke the move e4 with the bishop on d6. } 11. e4 Bh7 12. Qe2 e5 $11 ) ( 10. Nh4 { White is trying to go after the bishop on g4. } 10... Bh5 { We get ready to go ...g5 at any moment to get the bishop back to g6. } 11. b3 O-O 12. h3 Qe7 13. Bb2 Rad8 $11 ) 10... Qe7 11. b3 Bf5 { One big advantage with the bishop on d6 is that we have very good control over the e5 square. } 12. Qd2 Bc5 $11 { We will go ...Rd8 next with a comfortable position. } ) 6... Bh5 7. c4 dxc4 $1 { We go for the same sequence of moves we saw in the previous lines. We will not allow White to take on d5. Now there are not many pawn breaks available for White to open up the centre. } 8. dxc4 e6 9. Nc3 ( 9. Bf4 h6 { This will likely transpose to the main line. } 10. Qc1 $14 g5 11. Bd2 Bg7 { We take the chance to get the bishop to the long diagonal. White is not able to exploit it with the queen on c1. } 12. Rd1 Qe7 13. Nc3 Nh7 $11 { We stop ideas like h4 on the kingside. We can castle next move or go ...f5 and start playing on the kingside. } ) 9... h6 $1 { We have seen this a few times but here it is much more effective due to the pawn on h3. It allows us to go ...g4 soon to open the kingside. We are anticipating the move Bf4. } 10. Bf4 ( 10. Qc2 $14 { White delays putting his bishop on f4 but we are able to exploit it. } 10... Bd6 { We stop the move Bf4 and keep control over e5. } 11. Rd1 Qe7 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qd4 Bc5 15. Qe5 O-O $11 { We will get the rook to d8 next and equalise. } ) 10... Be7 { This is more flexible, keeping the option to go ...g5 open. We wait for White's next move. In some cases, we can just castle kingside. } 11. Qc1 { This has been played twice by Gelfand, B in online blitz games. It really shows his understanding and preparation as it is not the most intuitive move to play. We can still continue our play on the kingside but the queen keeps the bishop on e3 defended. } ( 11. Qc2 { This is a good example of why we waited for a move. We get a better version as the queen is misplaced on c2 here. } 11... g5 12. Be3 ( 12. Bd2 Bg6 13. e4 Qc7 $11 { We can castle queenside next and start attacking the kingside. } ) 12... g4 $1 { Here, we have the added motivation of getting to attack the bishop on e3. } 13. Nh4 gxh3 14. Bxh3 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Bxg4 16. Nf3 Qa5 $11 { We are going to swing the queen over to the kingside. We can also play ...h5-h4 and open the 'h' file. } ) 11... O-O $1 { In these lines, the queen is not doing much on c1. It would rather be on c2 to help bring the other rook into the game. This is the advantage of playing flexible moves- we do not need to show our hand early. } ( 11... g5 { is possible but less effective now. You can analyse it further. } ) 12. Rd1 ( 12. Nh4 { runs into } 12... Nh7 $11 ) ( 12. a3 { For every move of our opponent, we need to look for the drawbacks of that move. } 12... Nc5 $1 13. Qe3 a5 14. Rad1 Qb6 $11 { We will continue with Rad8 next with a balanced middlegame. } ) 12... Qb6 13. Nh4 { This is the best try for White to go after our bishop on the kingside. Otherwise, we will get the rook to d8 with a comfortable middlegame. } 13... Rfd8 ( 13... Rad8 { has been played but it is less accurate } 14. g4 Nh7 15. Bg3 g5 16. gxh5 gxh4 17. Bf4 $14 { and now White will take on h6 with a tempo, attacking the rook on f8. This happened in the game 1-0 (17) De, G (2352) -Sai Dinesh, G ICCF email 2020. } ) 14. g4 Nh7 $1 { This is our reaction to the move g4 in these lines. We attack the knight on h4 to get the g6 square for the bishop. } 15. Bg3 g5 $1 { Another important move to win the knight. } 16. gxh5 ( 16. Nf3 Bg6 $11 ) 16... gxh4 { Both sides have weakened their pawn structures on the kingside. We will quickly get our queen over to the kingside. } 17. Bf4 ( 17. Bh2 { this looks dangerous but we have } 17... Ndf6 $11 18. Qxh6 $2 Ng4 $1 19. hxg4 Bg5 $19 ) 17... Ndf6 18. Bxh6 ( 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Bxh6 Nxh5 20. Bf3 N5f6 $11 { The queen does a good job at keeping an eye on the f2 pawn. Our king will be reasonably safe on h8 with the knights on the kingside. } ) 18... Rxd1+ 19. Nxd1 Qa5 $1 20. Nc3 Qxh5 $11 { The position remains complex with chances for both sides. The good thing about this line is that it is virtually unexplored and I do not expect most of your opponents to know anything starting from move 8 or so. Then it can be pretty dangerous for White. } *

