1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 { In this chapter we will look at a few setups where White allows us to get control over the centre. He will generally play in the style of the KID and slowly prepare for the e4 break. } 4. O-O ( 4. b3 { We will see this structure in more detail in the 1.b3 chapter but there we have the bishop on f5 instead of g4. } 4... Nf6 5. Bb2 e6 6. O-O Bd6 { The bishop is better here to prepare the move ...e5. There is less danger of White going e4-e5 quickly. } 7. c4 { This is the more common plan when White goes for the move b3. He keeps both the diagonals open for the bishops but we have a very solid structure in the centre and will try to get the move ...e5. } ( 7. d3 { White hints at preparing the move e4 but it is pretty slow as he has wasted a couple of moves to get the bishop to b2. } 7... O-O 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. h3 Bh5 10. e4 e5 { We have spent two moves to get the pawn to e5 but it is easily worth it as we have better control over the centre. White can hardly release the tension as it gives us two very strong pawns in the middle of the board. } 11. Qe1 Re8 12. Nh4 a5 { A common plan whenever White goes for the move b3. We would love to get the pawn to a4 and a3. } 13. a3 Qc7 { The queen is ideally placed here as we are going to start playing on the queenside with ...b5 next. } 14. Nf5 Bf8 15. Kh1 g6 $5 { We are trying to exploit the knight on f5. } ( 15... dxe4 { is a simpler option } 16. dxe4 b5 $11 ) 16. Nh4 g5 $1 { We gain space on the kingside too. It helps us stop any play with f4 and White cannot really exploit it. } 17. Nhf3 h6 $11 ) 7... Nbd7 8. d3 ( 8. d4 { We will see these structures in the upcoming chapters. They are pretty comfortable for Black. } 8... O-O $11 ) 8... O-O 9. Nbd2 h6 { This is a useful move on the kingside and it creates a square on h7 for the bishop whenever needed. } 10. Qc2 ( 10. h3 Bh5 11. a3 a5 12. Qc2 Bg6 { We take the sting out of the move e4. He can go for it but cannot advance further. It will come under fire. } 13. e4 dxe4 14. dxe4 Qb6 15. Rab1 Bh7 16. Bd4 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Nxc5 $11 ) 10... e5 $1 { We are now able to bring the bishop back to e6. Earlier it could be met with Ng5 but we have covered it with our previous move. } 11. h3 Be6 $11 { We are clearly on the better side of equality. } ) 4... Nd7 5. d3 ( 5. b3 { This is a worse version of the lines we saw earlier as we are able to immediately get control over the centre. } 5... e5 6. Bb2 Bd6 7. d3 Ngf6 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. e4 Re8 10. h3 Bh5 11. Qe1 ( 11. Re1 { This was one of my first games in this structure against a strong opponent and I ended up releasing the tension very early. } 11... a5 ( 11... dxe4 { was unnecessary in the game: 1-0 (45) Jones, G (2654) -Arjun, K (2419) London 2017. } ) 12. a3 h6 $15 { We will continue slowly with ...Bg6 and ...b5 next. } ) 11... a5 12. a3 Qc7 $15 { We will continue playing on the queenside with ...b5, ...a4 and ...c5 next. } ) 5... Ngf6 { Once again, White has the dilemma of whether to or not to include the moves h3 and ...Bh5. There are two ways to prepare for the move e4- Nbd2 or Qe1. We will see the Qe1 plan in this chapter. } 6. h3 { This makes a lot of sense to make sure that we do not retreat to e6 as we saw earlier. } ( 6. Nbd2 { This is the main line in the position and will be checked in the next chapter. } ) ( 6. Qe1 e5 7. e4 dxe4 $1 { We do not usually trade on e4 but we have a very concrete reason here. We are able to retreat to e6 with a threat of ...Bc4. } 8. dxe4 Qc7 { We keep all the options open when it comes to the dark-squared bishop. } ( 8... Bc5 { is the usual move but I think we need to be more flexible. } 9. Nbd2 { Now, we are not in time to get the bishop to e6. } 9... h6 10. Nc4 Qc7 11. b4 $36 ) 9. Nbd2 ( 9. h3 Be6 10. Qe2 h6 $11 ) 9... h6 $1 { Now, we need to stop White's plan of h3 and Ng5. } 10. Nc4 ( 10. Nh4 Be6 11. Nf5 g6 12. Ne3 a5 $11 ) 10... Be6 11. Qe2 Bc5 $36 { We will continue with ..b5 and ...a5 on the queenside. Usually, our bishop is misplaced on the kingside but we have managed to solve the issue here. } ) 6... Bh5 7. Qe1 { This is a better version for White with the bishop stuck on h5. } 7... e5 8. e4 Bd6 { This is more effective against the Qe1 plan as we do not need to worry about the knight coming to c4 quickly. It keeps the e5 pawn more secure. } ( 8... Be7 { This was the main line of my analysis and I have played a couple of games here. However, after a painful loss against Esipenko, I felt that this was slightly unpleasant to play over the board. I have given my analysis and you can take a look if you want to. } 9. exd5 ( 9. Nc3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 dxe4 11. dxe4 ( 11. Nxe4 Nd5 12. a3 ( 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 f5 14. Nd2 Bc5 ) 12... O-O 13. Rb1 ( 13. b4 a5 $11 ) 13... a5 14. Nc3 Nc7 15. b4 Ne6 16. Bg2 axb4 17. axb4 h5 18. h4 Nd4 $11 ) 11... Nc5 12. Nd1 O-O 13. Ne3 Re8 14. Nf5 Bf8 15. Bg5 Ne6 16. Qc1 Nxg5 17. Qxg5 Kh8 18. Rad1 Qc7 19. Nh6 Ng8 20. Nxg8 Kxg8 $11 ) 9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nxd5 11. Nd2 ( 11. Nc3 Nc7 $1 ( 11... Nxc3 { 1-0 (43) Esipenko,A (2678) -Arjun,K (2505) Sitges 2022 } ) 12. Bg4 O-O 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Qxe5 Bd6 15. Qh5 f5 16. Ne2 Ne6 $11 ) 11... O-O 12. Nc4 ( 12. Bg2 f5 $11 ) 12... Qc7 13. Ne3 Nxe3 14. Bxe3 f5 $11 15. Qc3 Kh8 ) 9. Nh4 { This is a natural reaction to the bishop on d6. In addition, White is also keeping an eye on the d5 pawn } ( 9. Nbd2 { This is the most common move here but mixing both the plans is not great, especially with the bishop on d6. } 9... O-O 10. Nh4 ( 10. exd5 { This would have been critical with the queen still on d1. Now, it is a big error. } 10... cxd5 11. c4 $6 Nc5 $17 ) 10... Re8 { We vacate the f8 square for one of our pieces and keep an eye on the 'e' file. } 11. Nf5 Bc7 { I like this more with the plan of going ...Nf8-e6 next. I do not see a good plan for White to create any play. } 12. Nb3 a5 13. a4 Nf8 $15 ) ( 9. exd5 { We need to take a look at this with our king still in the middle of the board. } 9... Nxd5 { We are not able to bring our 'c' pawn towards the centre but now we can go for the move ...f6 to hold our centre together. } 10. Nxe5 { This is the most tempting move and has been played by a few strong players (including a young Gukesh) . } ( 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Nh4 Ne7 $11 { We cover the f5 square and prepare to go ...f5 ourselves. } ) 10... Nxe5 11. d4 O-O 12. dxe5 Re8 13. f4 f6 { We are winning the e5 pawn and our pieces are better placed. However, all three of the games ended in White's favour (White players were higher rated though) . } 14. Nc3 ( 14. Nd2 { We need to exploit the drawback of this move. } 14... Qb6+ $1 ( 14... fxe5 15. f5 { 1-0 (42) Howell,D (2689) -Brunello,S (2552) Batumi 2018 } ) 15. Kh1 Ne3 { We attack a bunch of pieces. } 16. Ne4 Nxg2 $1 { We end up just going after the crucial light-squared bishop which was holding White's position together. } 17. Kxg2 Bc7 $36 ) ( 14. e6 { This was a significant error by Gukesh. } 14... f5 15. Bd2 Qf6 $19 { would have just won the 'e' pawn. } ( 15... Qb6+ { 1-0 (25) Gukesh, D (2466) -Shrey, N (1466) Mumbai 2018 } ) ) 14... fxe5 15. f5 { This is a typical idea to keep the 'e' file closed. } 15... Bc5+ { It is better to include this check here. } ( 15... Nxc3 { 1-0 (30) Berkes,F (2648) -Swapnil,S (2534) Moscow 2017 } ) 16. Kh1 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 Bd4 $36 { We will try to get in the move e4 next and open the centre for our rooks. } ) 9... O-O 10. g4 Bg6 11. g5 { This is a very critical line which we need to know properly. } ( 11. Nc3 dxe4 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. g5 { This is necessary as White should not block the diagonal for the bishop. } 13... Nd5 14. Qxe4 Ne7 $11 { We will continue with either ...Nc5-e6 or go for the move ... f5. } ) 11... Nh5 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Nxg6 { White needs to eliminate the bishop immediately. We have two ways to recapture. } ( 13. Bxd5 $2 { is bad after } 13... Nf4 $17 { and the g5 pawn is a big issue for White. } ) 13... fxg6 { This is the more natural move, keeping the 'f' file open for the rook. f2 is a big target for us. } 14. Bxd5+ ( 14. Nc3 d4 15. Ne4 Be7 $11 ) 14... Kh8 15. Nc3 ( 15. Qe4 Nf4 16. Bxf4 Rxf4 17. Qg2 Be7 $11 { White cannot defend the g5 pawn. } ) 15... Nf4 16. Bxf4 Rxf4 17. Bxb7 { White gives up the 'g' pawn but wins the b7 pawn. We need to prove our compensation for the pawn now. } ( 17. Ne4 { runs into } 17... Nc5 $15 ) 17... Qxg5+ 18. Bg2 Raf8 19. Ne4 Qe7 { If given the chance, we will regroup the bishop to b6 via c7. } 20. Qa5 ( 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. Qe3 Nc5 { We will bring the knight to e6, move the rook back, and get our knight to f4. } 22. Rae1 R4f5 23. c3 Ne6 24. d4 Nf4 25. dxe5 Qe6 $40 { We have an attack brewing on the kingside. We can bring both the rooks into the attack via f5. } ) 20... Nf6 { We want to trade the knights and get into an opposite colour bishop middlegame where the side who is attacking has a huge edge. } 21. Nxd6 { This is the only move to maintain equality. } 21... Qxd6 22. Rae1 Rf5 $44 { We will bring the knight to f4 via h5 next. We have enough compensation for the pawn. } *

