1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Nd7 5. d3 Ngf6 6. h3 { White forces the bishop to h5 and also ensures that he can go g4 in one go. } ( 6. Nbd2 { This is the most played move in the position but it will usually transpose to the lines with the inclusion of h3 and ...Bh5. } 6... e5 7. e4 Be7 $1 { This has been played in less than 60 games out of more than 2400 games. We maintain the tension and look to castle next. The drawback is that our e5 pawn is more exposed and we do need to keep an eye out for it. } 8. exd5 ( 8. h3 Bh5 { transposes. } ) 8... Nxd5 9. Nc4 ( 9. Re1 O-O $11 { White will have to go h3 and g4 which will transpose. } ) 9... Qc7 ( 9... O-O { is possible but I do not want to give up the bishop so easily. } 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qc7 $11 ) 10. Qe1 ( 10. Qe2 f6 { We are going to castle next move. Even if White goes d4 to win the e5 pawn it will end up opening up the 'f' file for our rook. } 11. Ne3 Nxe3 12. Qxe3 O-O 13. d4 Bd6 14. Qb3+ Kh8 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 $11 ) 10... f6 11. Qe4 Bh5 { The bishop will go to g6 next to kick the queen back. White has to be careful here as we can easily take over the position with our centre. } 12. d4 O-O 13. dxe5 fxe5 14. Ncxe5 Rae8 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Ne5 Qe6 $44 { We have ample compensation for the pawn with our lead in development. We will put our bishop on c5 next and target the f2 pawn. } ) 6... Bh5 7. Nbd2 e5 8. e4 Be7 { This works here because White is not putting pressure on the e5 pawn as in the previous line. We will maintain the tension for as long as possible. White can go after the e5 pawn but it will give us a lead in development. } ( 8... Bd6 { does not work so well here with the knight on d2. } 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nc4 $14 { [%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1] } ) 9. Qe1 { This is the more common move but it is not the best objectively. White cannot win the e5 pawn and otherwise, slow play is not the right way to go. } ( 9. Re1 O-O { If there is an option, I prefer to maintain the tension in the centre. } ( 9... dxe4 { is possible but there is no need. } 10. dxe4 Qc7 11. Nc4 O-O $11 ) 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nc4 ( 12. Nxe5 { can be met with } 12... Nxe5 13. Rxe5 Nf4 { We want to win the light-squared bishop which holds White's kingside together. } 14. Qf3 Nxg2 15. Qxg2 f5 $36 { We will continue with either ...Bc5 or ...Bh4 and go after the f2 pawn. } ) 12... f6 13. d4 { White tries to exploit the weakness created by our previous move on e6. } 13... Qc7 $1 { We still continue to maintain the tension. White can win the e5 pawn but it will allow us to go after the pawn on f2. } 14. Nh4 { White immediately goes after our dark-squared bishop on e7 with Nf5 coming next. } ( 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nfxe5 fxe5 $36 { [%cal Gf8f2,Ge7c5] } ) ( 14. Ne3 Nxe3 15. Bxe3 Rfd8 16. Nh4 Bf7 17. Nf5 Bb4 { We are provoking the move c3 as it weakens the d3 square. We want to get our knight to e5. } 18. c3 Bf8 $11 ) 14... Bf7 15. Nf5 Bb4 16. c3 { It looks like our bishop is stuck but we are able to exploit our lead in development. } 16... Nxc3 $1 17. bxc3 Bxc3 18. d5 Bxa1 19. Ba3 cxd5 20. Bxd5 Bd4 21. Bd6 Qd8 22. Be7 Qc7 $11 { An unusual repetition but both sides do not have much choice here. Our queen lacks a good square on the board. } ) 9... O-O 10. Nh4 { This is the most played move but as I mentioned, White does not get anything when he plays slowly. We have better control over the centre and the option to release the tension at any point in time. } ( 10. exd5 { This does not achieve anything here other than giving us great control over the centre. } 10... Nxd5 11. g4 { This is again bad as White is really lagging in the development of his queenside. } ( 11. Nxe5 $2 { is met strongly with } 11... Nb4 $19 ) 11... Bg6 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Qxe5 Bd6 14. Qe1 Qd7 $15 { We will continue with ...Rae8 next and the . ..f5 break on the kingside. } ) 10... Re8 11. Nb3 ( 11. Nf5 { The knight does not actually achieve much on f5. } 11... Bf8 12. Nb3 ( 12. Nf3 Nc5 $15 ) ( 12. g4 Bg6 13. Qe2 Bxf5 14. gxf5 g6 $15 { We want to get our knight to h5. We can take over the position on the kingside next. } ) 12... a5 13. a4 h6 $11 { We are preparing to go ...Bg6 next and kick the knight back. We create a luft for the bishop on h7 anticipating the move Nh4. We are on the better side of equality. } ) 11... a5 12. a4 b6 { I like this move more, asking White how he wants to continue. Now, we can move the rook from the 'a' file or bring it into the game via a7. } ( 12... Nc5 $11 { is the usual move which I played in a Titled Tuesday game, 1-0 (78) Piesik,P (2418) -Arjun,K (2477) Chess.com INT 2020. } ) 13. Be3 Rb8 14. g4 { White goes for his play on the kingside. } 14... Bg6 15. f4 dxe4 16. f5 Nd5 17. fxg6 hxg6 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Ge3f2,Re4e3,Re3e2] The knight on h4 is trapped and White is unable to defend it with Bf2 due to the move ...e3. } 18. Nxg6 fxg6 19. Bxe4 Bh4 20. Qe2 Bg5 21. Bd2 Bxd2 22. Nxd2 Re6 $11 { The position is complex but I like our position with ...Nc5 and ...Nf4 coming up next. It happened in the game- 1/2-1/2 (34) Dearnley,A (2368) -Ballow,J (2416) ICCF email 2015. } *

