1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Nd7 5. d4 { We are going to see these d4 structures in this chapter and the next. There is a big difference in the move order though. It is more critical with the inclusion of the moves h3 and ... Bh5 which we will take a look at in the next chapter. The key difference is that now we are able to retreat to f5 in many cases. } 5... e6 6. c4 ( 6. h3 { This is a natural question if White is able to transpose to the next chapter. } 6... Bxf3 $5 { The answer is no as we give up the bishop on f3. White having played the move d4 comes back to hurt him. It is much better to keep the centre open when he gets the bishop pair. } ( 6... Bh5 { This is the safer option which will transpose to the next chapter. } ) 7. Bxf3 ( 7. exf3 { Now, he will not be able to break in the centre easily. } 7... Bd6 { We are going to develop the knight to e7 next. } 8. f4 Ne7 9. Nd2 b5 $11 { We stop the move c4. We will break with the move ...c5 soon. } ) 7... f5 $1 { We get an excellent version of the Stonewall having traded off the light-squared bishop which is supposed to be the main issue for Black. Also, the bishop is misplaced on f3 and it will take a long time for him to develop his pieces properly. We could go ...g5 on the kingside and start attacking. } 8. Bf4 { This is the critical move, stopping ...Bd6. } ( 8. c4 Bd6 9. Qb3 Rb8 { We have stopped the move Bf4 and will continue with ...Ngf6 and ...Qe7 next. The king can remain in the centre or go to f7. } ) 8... Qf6 $1 { We are preparing to kick the bishop away next. } 9. c4 g5 10. Bh5+ Kd8 { Our king is not in much danger here. } 11. Bd2 Bd6 12. Nc3 Ne7 13. e3 Qh6 14. Kg2 Nf6 { We finally kick the bishop back. } 15. Be2 Qg6 16. cxd5 exd5 17. b4 f4 $40 { The position is very complicated. We can go ...Rf8 next and get the knight to f5. } ) ( 6. b3 { This is too slow in conjunction with the move d4 giving us a very comfortable middlegame. } 6... Ngf6 7. Bb2 Be7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. c4 { This has been seen in quite a few games but this structure is harmless when we have the bishop outside the pawn chain. } 9... a5 { A common idea with the pawn on b3. The pawn on a4 would be a nuisance for White. } 10. a3 h6 { We will now retreat to f5 when attacked. So we create a luft for the bishop on h7. } 11. Re1 Bf5 $11 ) ( 6. Nbd2 { White wants to get the e4 break. He will not play the move c4 here. } 6... Ngf6 7. Re1 ( 7. h3 Bh5 { This is a rare case where we retreat to h5 after White has gone for the move d4. White is able to go Nh4 immediately if we go to f5. However, as he has already played the move Nd2, it is not very critical. } 8. Re1 ( 8. c4 { With the knight on d2, this gives us a comfortable position. } 8... Be7 9. b3 Ne4 $36 { We are ready to go ...f5 next. } ) 8... Be7 9. e4 h6 $11 { We create a square on h7 for the knight. We will see this idea in more detail in the main line as we are likely to transpose soon. } ) 7... Be7 { We will ignore the move e4 and continue developing our pieces. We have managed to get our bishop outside the pawn chain which is a big achievement in these positions. } 8. e4 h6 $5 { This has been played in only 30 odd games, compared to the 500+ games in both ...O-O and ...dxe4. We create a square on h7 for our knight as White can go ...e5 anytime. Otherwise, we will castle kingside next. } 9. c3 ( 9. b3 { This has never been played before. The bishop is not doing much on b2. } 9... O-O 10. Bb2 a5 { Our usual idea whenever White puts his pawn on b3. } 11. h3 Bh5 12. c4 a4 $11 ) ( 9. e5 Nh7 10. h3 ( 10. Nf1 Ng5 { We trade the knights the first chance we get. } 11. h4 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Bf5 $11 { Our bishop is a better minor piece here along this diagonal. } ) 10... Bh5 11. c4 Ng5 12. b3 O-O 13. h4 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Bg6 $11 { The bishop is well placed here. We will go for the move ... f6 next and open up the 'f' file. } ) 9... O-O { We will next continue playing on the queenside with moves like ...a5 and ...b5. White will have to decide what he wants to do with the e4 pawn. } 10. h3 ( 10. Qb3 Qc7 11. e5 Nh7 $11 { We will go ...a5-a4 kicking the queen back, followed by the move ...c5. } ) ( 10. e5 Nh7 11. Nb3 a5 $11 { This is a very common move whenever a piece or pawn lands on b3. } ) 10... Bh5 11. e5 Nh7 { The knight will come to g5 next. We will focus our play on the queenside with ...c5 and ...b5. } 12. Nf1 ( 12. h4 c5 13. dxc5 { This happened in the game 1-0 (35) Kuzubov, Y (2627) -Carlsson, P (2496) Dubai 2011. Black is doing very well after } 13... Bxc5 $15 ) ( 12. Qb3 Qc7 13. Nf1 c5 14. Bf4 Rfc8 15. Rac1 { This happened in one of my games 0-1 (74) Venkatesh, M (2493) -Arjun, K (2477) Chess.com INT 2020. I had a big advantage after } 15... c4 16. Qd1 b5 $17 { with easy play on the queenside. } ) 12... Ng5 { We will take on f3 and put the bishop on g6. It is a very annoying piece along the diagonal. } 13. Bxg5 Bxg5 14. g4 Bg6 15. Nxg5 Qxg5 16. Qd2 { White wants to go for the move f4 next. } 16... f5 $11 { We want to open up the 'f' file and take control of the f4 square. } ) 6... Ngf6 7. h3 { Finally we see what happens if White tries to transpose to the next chapter once again. As we saw earlier, we have no reason to allow that. } ( 7. Ne5 { We have seen this plan already. We can transpose back or we have an extra option here. } 7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 Nd7 { It is not easy to keep the e5 pawn alive. } 9. cxd5 exd5 10. h3 Bf5 11. f4 f6 $11 { We are going after White's centre. We want to get full control over the e4 square. } ) ( 7. cxd5 { This is the critical try with the inclusion of the move h3 but as I mentioned, not very dangerous here. } 7... exd5 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. Qe3+ Be7 { We will see this in the next chapter where this pin is quite annoying. Here we have a simple solution to this issue. } 10. Nc3 Be6 $1 { The bishop comes back to e6 to enable us to castle kingside. } ( 10... h6 $5 { is also possible to prepare the move ...Be6 but it gives White time to create something on the kingside. } 11. Nh4 Be6 12. f4 $13 ) 11. Ng5 { This is the natural response but the knight will be kicked back soon enough. } 11... Bf5 { This is a better square for the bishop compared to g4. We can either go ...h6 next or go ...Qd8 followed by 0-0. } 12. b3 Qd8 13. Ba3 h6 14. Nf3 Be6 $11 { We will castle next with a comfortable position. White is not in time to create anything. } ) ( 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. c5 { This is a popular plan but does not lead to anything for White. } 8... Qxb3 9. axb3 Be7 10. b4 a6 11. Nc3 Bxf3 $1 { We give up the bishop voluntarily on f3 as White had the option to go Nd2-b3-a5 on the queenside. } ( 11... O-O 12. Nd2 $1 ) 12. Bxf3 O-O 13. Bf4 Rfe8 $11 { We will go ...Bf8 next move and prepare to go either ...g5 or ...e5 next. } ) 7... Bf5 $1 { The bishop can directly head to the h7-b1 diagonal. This is much better than having to put the bishop on h5. The bishop can go to e4 if White goes Nh4. } 8. Nc3 h6 { We create a luft for the bishop on h7 and stop all of White's ideas on the kingside. } 9. Nd2 { White wants to get the move e4 to open up the centre. It is not a big deal as we too get a target on d4 to play against. } ( 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. c5 Qxb3 11. axb3 a6 12. b4 { We need to be careful not to allow White to get the move b5 easily. } 12... Ne4 { We trade the knight on c3 to stop his play on the queenside. } 13. Nd2 Nxd2 $1 { Now, it is more important to stop the plan of Nd2-b3-a5. There are many ways to stop the b5 plan. } 14. Bxd2 Rd8 $11 ) 9... Be7 10. e4 dxe4 11. Ndxe4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Nf6 { We want to trade as many pieces as possible as we have less space. The major piece endgames are in our favour as we can go after the d4 pawn. } 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Be3 a6 { We want to go for the move ...b5 on the queenside. } 15. Qe2 ( 15. a3 b5 $1 16. Bxc6 bxc4 { We are happy to sacrifice the exchange as we win the valuable light-squared bishop. } 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18. Kh2 Rb8 $15 { It is not easy to defend the b2 pawn. We are going to go ...Rb3 next followed by ...Qb7. } ) 15... Rc8 16. Rac1 b5 { We want to trade the c4 pawn to get the d5 square for the knight. It would leave the d4 pawn isolated in the centre. } 17. Rfd1 bxc4 18. Qxc4 Nd5 $11 { We want to win the dark-squared bishop on e3 as it would weaken White's kingside. The d5 square compensates for our weak pawns on the queenside. } *

