1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Nd7 5. h3 { As we saw in the previous chapter, this is the more critical move here, forcing us to make the choice very early. White can then play according to the choice we make. } 5... Bh5 { This is the best option away from ideas of Nh4 but this means that we are not able to bring the bishop back to e6 or f5. So, the same lines we saw last chapter are more dangerous now. } ( 5... Bf5 { has its own issues as White can go } 6. Nh4 $14 ) 6. d4 e6 7. c4 Ngf6 8. cxd5 { This is the most common move here. We have to decide how to recapture on d5. With the knight on b8 we saw ...cxd5 but it is much less effective here with the knight already on d7. } ( 8. Qb3 { These lines do not lead to anything for White. To fight for an advantage, he needs to imbalance the pawn structure first. } 8... Qb6 9. Nc3 ( 9. cxd5 Qxb3 $1 { We do not allow White to get his queen over to e3. } 10. axb3 exd5 $11 ) 9... h6 { We want to make sure White cannot win our bishop with Nh4 and g4. It is always a useful move in any case to prepare a future ...g5. This has been played in only one game out of more than 40 games. } 10. Be3 Bg6 11. c5 Qxb3 12. axb3 Be7 13. b4 Ne4 $11 { We stop b5 by trading off the knight on c3. } ) ( 8. Nc3 { This is a tricky move to face here. With the inclusion of the moves cxd5 and .. .exd5 we put our bishop on d6. Here, it is not as effective. } 8... dxc4 $1 { We exploit White's move order. It is not easy to win back the pawn now. } ( 8... Bd6 9. Qb3 $14 { Going for the move ...Qb6 is less pleasant here as White gets c5 with a tempo attacking the bishop on d6. } ) ( 8... Be7 { is also not great due to } 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Ne5 $14 ) 9. e4 Bb4 10. Qe2 Bxf3 $14 { We give up the bishop before White can go g4 and Ne5 on the kingside. } 11. Bxf3 b5 12. a4 a6 13. e5 Nd5 14. Bxd5 cxd5 15. Qg4 $1 { This is the only way for White to maintain equality. Otherwise, we castle and he has no compensation for the pawn. } 15... g6 16. Bg5 Be7 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. axb5 O-O 19. Rxa6 Rxa6 20. bxa6 Ra8 $11 { We will win back the pawn soon. White is not close to creating anything on the kingside. } ) ( 8. Ne5 { We saw this plan earlier but only without the inclusion of the move h3. The difference is that the bishop is on h5 instead of on the b1-h7 diagonal. } 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Nc3 ( 11. Be3 Nxe5 12. Nc3 f6 $11 { We create a square on f7 for the bishop. We will try to develop our pieces and castle as soon as possible next. } ) ( 11. f4 Bc5+ 12. Kh2 O-O 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nc3 h5 $1 { We fight back in the queenside, hoping to force White to close down the kingside. } 15. e4 hxg4 16. exd5 gxh3 17. Bxh3 Qh4 { We go after his kingside preparing to go ...Bf5 next. } 18. Qg4 Qh7 $36 { The position is complex but I think White is risking more with his exposed king. } ) 11... Bc5 { We stop the move f4 and are ready to win the e5 pawn next. } 12. g4 Bg6 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 ( 14. Bf4 e3 15. fxe3 O-O $11 ) 14... Bxe4 { We give up the bishop as the knight on e4 is a superior piece and was heading to d6. } 15. Bxe4 Nxe5 16. Qa4+ ( 16. Bxb7 $6 { runs into } 16... Bxf2+ $1 ) 16... Qd7 17. Qxd7+ Nxd7 18. Bxb7 Rb8 19. Bg2 Ke7 $11 { We reach an equal endgame. In general White should have a small edge due to the bishop pair but our pieces are more active and better placed. We will cement the pawn on e5 and the bishop on d4. } ) 8... exd5 { We get an imbalance in the pawn structure. We want to go ...Bd6 and castle kingside next. White has a few ways to do something quickly before we achieve that. } 9. Qb3 { This is the most common move in the position. White can shift his queen along the 3rd rank to e3 at the right moment. } ( 9. Nc3 Bd6 $1 { Now that the pawns are traded on d5 we can get our bishop to its best square, controlling e5. Ne5 is a very frequent idea for White in these positions. } 10. Nh4 { This is the natural reaction to get the knight to f5, attacking the bishop on d6. } ( 10. Nd2 { White is preparing to go for the move e4 in the centre. The immediate threat is to go g4 and f4 on the kingside. } 10... Bg6 11. e4 { This leads to a lot of simplifications. } ( 11. f4 Qb6 $1 { The d4 pawn is hard to defend. } 12. e3 Bd3 $15 ) 11... dxe4 12. Ncxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 { We give up our bishop but in return, we will get control over the d5 square. We are playing against the IQP on d4. } ( 13... Be7 14. Nc3 $16 { [%cal Gd4d5] } ) 14. Bxe4 Nf6 15. Bf3 { This is the best square for the bishop keeping the g2 square open for the king. } 15... O-O 16. Kg2 Re8 17. Be3 Be7 $11 { We will put the knight on d5 next and the bishop will go to f6. } ) ( 10. Qb3 { is not a big issue for us after the trade on d5. } 10... Qb6 11. Nh4 Bg6 12. Qd1 O-O 13. Nxg6 { White does win the bishop pair but it is not so important in this middlegame with the centre blocked. The bishop on g2 is not very active. } 13... hxg6 14. Qd3 Rfe8 15. h4 Nf8 $11 { The knight will come to e6 next, targeting the d4 pawn. } ) 10... O-O 11. Qd3 { White defends the g3 pawn and is ready to go f4 next. } ( 11. Nf5 Bc7 $11 { The bishop is doing pretty well on c7. We will get our rook to e8 next and eventually kick the knight back after ...Bg6. } ) ( 11. f4 { This does look very dangerous as White is threatening to go g4 and f5 trapping the bishop. We need to maintain our composure in such situations. } 11... Bg6 $1 { We want to get our bishop to e4 now. White is not able to go f5 yet as the g3 pawn is hanging. } 12. g4 Be4 13. g5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Ne8 $11 { The exchange of light-squared bishops is a big positive for us. We will put our knight on b6, anticipating White to play e4 and we get the knight to d5. } ) 11... Be7 $14 { This is an unusual move but our point is that we want the option of going ...Ne8-d6 if White starts pushing his pawns on the kingside. We keep an eye on the h4 knight. } 12. f4 ( 12. f3 { is pretty slow and we can go } 12... Re8 13. Be3 Nb6 { [%cal Gf6d7] } ) 12... Ne8 13. Nf5 Bb4 { We will go ...Bg6 and take on c3 if needed. } 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Bg6 16. Nh6+ $5 gxh6 17. f5 Nc5 $1 { We are in time to get rid of the dangerous knight on e4. } 18. Qc4 Nxe4 19. fxg6 hxg6 20. Bxh6 N8f6 21. Qxb4 Re8 $11 { I like our position with the knights in the middle of the board. } ) ( 9. Nh4 { White wants to get the knight to f5 as soon as possible, exploiting the bishop on h5. } 9... Be7 ( 9... Bg6 { is the main line but I do not see any reason to give up the bishop so easily. } ) 10. Nf5 ( 10. Nc3 { White keeps the plan of Nf5 in the air. } 10... O-O 11. Nf5 ( 11. f4 { He wants to go g4 and win the piece on h5. } 11... Ne8 12. Nf5 Bb4 $11 { The bishop indirectly fights for the centre, keeping an eye on the c3 knight. } ) ( 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bf4 Nb6 $11 { We can go .. .Bd6 next and trade off the dark-squared bishops. } ) 11... Bb4 $1 { We will rather give up our bishop for the knight on c3 which is keeping control over e4. We will bring our rook to e8 and target the e2 pawn. } 12. Bf4 Re8 $36 { [%csl Rc3,Re2] } ) 10... Bg6 $1 { We immediately force the knight to trade on e7. He has wasted several moves for this trade and in return, we have good control over the centre. } 11. Nxe7 ( 11. Nxg7+ $6 Kf8 12. Bh6 Kg8 $15 { [%cal Ge7f8] } ) 11... Qxe7 12. Qb3 Nb6 13. Bd2 { This is the critical try to stop us from castling kingside. It was played against me by Adhiban in an online rapid game. I was prepared though as this is the top choice of computers. } ( 13. Qa3 { This was played in a corr game but I think the endgame is pretty balanced. } 13... Qxa3 14. Nxa3 O-O 15. Re1 Rfe8 16. Bd2 a5 { This is a useful move to gain space on the queenside. } 17. h4 h5 $11 { Next, we will go ...Nfd7 and bring the knight to e6. We will put our pawn on f6. } ) 13... Ne4 14. Bb4 Qc7 15. Bxe4 { This was the main line of my analysis. } ( 15. Nd2 a5 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bc5 { This was an inaccuracy but I failed to react properly. I remember I had just lot a couple of games and was not feeling very confident. } ( 17. Bd6 { I knew this move which is the best here. We have to repeat after } 17... Qxd6 18. Qxb6 Qb4 19. Qc7 Qe7 20. Qb6 Qb4 $11 ) 17... Nd5 $1 { We are not too concerned about the bishop on c5. } ( 17... Nd7 $16 { was bad in the game 1-0 (38) Adhiban, B (2603) -Arjun, K (2529) chess24.com INT 2022. } ) 18. f3 f5 $36 { We can actually castle queenside next. Black has a very comfortable position. } ) 15... Bxe4 16. Nc3 { This is more critical as White can put more pressure on the queenside here with the knight more active compared to d2. } ( 16. Nd2 O-O-O $13 { Our king is reasonably safe on b8. We will start attacking on the kingside as White lacks the light-squared bishop. } ) 16... Qd7 { We immediately start our play on the kingside here. There is no time to waste. } 17. h4 ( 17. Bc5 Qxh3 18. Nxe4 dxe4 $36 { We will castle next and continue with ...h5-h4. } ) 17... g5 $1 { The position gets very complex now. } 18. h5 Qh3 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Bc5 O-O-O 21. Bxb6 axb6 22. Rac1 $1 ( 22. Qxb6 { can be met with } 22... e3 $36 ) 22... Rd6 23. Qxf7 Rh6 $1 { White is forced to go for a draw now. He cannot stop ...Rh5 and mate on the kingside. } 24. Qg7 Rxh5 25. Qxh8+ Kc7 26. Qg7+ Kb8 27. Qf8+ Ka7 28. Qa3+ Kb8 $11 ) ( 9. Ne5 { This is a popular and critical move which was played at the highest level in the Candidates. This is pretty different compared to the Ne5 lines we checked in the earlier chapter. The bishop would much rather be on the c8-h3 diagonal rather than on h5. } 9... Ne4 $1 { A very important move to remember. We get the knight to e4 before White has time to get his knight to c3. } 10. Bxe4 { This has been played several times by GM Svane Rasmus from Germany including against me in an online game. } ( 10. Qb3 { can be met with } 10... Nxe5 11. Bxe4 Bxe2 12. Re1 Bc4 13. Qxb7 Rb8 14. Qxa7 Ra8 { and it is a forced draw by repetition. } ) ( 10. Nd2 { This is the more complicated try for White. } 10... f5 $1 { We maintain the tension with the knight in the centre. } 11. Nxe4 ( 11. g4 $14 { White tries to destabilise our control over the centre. } 11... Nxd2 12. Bxd2 Nxe5 13. dxe5 fxg4 { We are happy to be able to win the 'g' pawn. Now White's kingside is pretty exposed. } 14. Qb3 Qc8 $36 ) ( 11. Bf3 { This was played in a Titled Tuesday game by Yu, Y but we get a good position after } 11... Bg6 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Bg2 Nf6 $11 { We have great control over the centre with the pawn on e4. } ) 11... fxe4 12. Bf4 { This was tried by Grischuk against Keymar who is an expert in this line. Black has to play accurately here. } ( 12. Kh1 $14 Be7 13. f3 O-O { We are ready to take on e5 next move. } 14. fxe4 Rxf1+ 15. Qxf1 Nxe5 16. dxe5 d4 $36 { [%csl Re2,Re4,Re5] White's structure is completely ruined. } ) ( 12. g4 $14 { can be met with } 12... Nxe5 13. gxh5 Nc4 14. f3 exf3 15. Bxf3 Be7 $11 { We will castle next with a good position. Both sides have chances here with White's bishop pair and development compensating for his exposed kingside. } ) ( 12. f4 Be7 13. Kh2 O-O 14. Bd2 a5 $11 { We stop the move b4. Next we can go for the ...c5 break. We also have the potential plan of going g5 on the kingside. } ) 12... g5 $1 { We want to take on e5 next and force him to recapture with a pawn. } ( 12... Be7 { gave White some edge in 1-0 (63) Grischuk,A (2745) -Keymer,V (2700) Astana 2023. } ) 13. Be3 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qe7 $11 { We will go ...Bg7 and castle kingside next. } ) 10... dxe4 ( 10... Nxe5 { I mixed up the move order in my game 0-1 (70) Svane, R (2651) -Arjun, K (2477) Chess.com INT 2022 and this gives White a few different ways to press. } 11. Bg2 { [%cal Gb1c3,Gd1b3] } ) 11. Nc3 Be7 { We maintain the tension for now and focus on our development, preparing to get our king to safety quickly. } ( 11... f6 { is an option but more complex. } ) 12. Bf4 ( 12. Nxe4 { is met with } 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bxe2 15. Nd6+ Bxd6 16. Rxd6 Rd8 $11 { with an equal endgame. } ) 12... Nxe5 { We now need to defend the e4 pawn. We first trade the knights. } ( 12... O-O 13. Nxe4 $14 ) 13. dxe5 Bg6 { We have the bishop pair now but our weakness on e4 compensates for it. } 14. Qb3 ( 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Rfd1 h5 $11 ) 14... Qb6 15. Rfd1 h5 { A typical move, gaining space in the kingside and stopping the move g4. } 16. Be3 Qxb3 17. axb3 a5 18. Kg2 Bb4 19. Rd4 O-O $11 { We will go ...Re8 next and go after e5. } ) 9... Qb6 10. Qe3+ { The main point of this is to prevent us from castling easily. We will have to bring the queen back to d8 to defend e7 or find another way. Again, the bishop on g4 would have been helpful as we could just bring it back to e6. } 10... Be7 11. Nh4 ( 11. Nc3 Bg6 12. b3 Ne4 { We solve our issue along the 'e' file pretty easily as we can castle the next move. } 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. dxe5 O-O $11 { The endgame is even with both the pawn on e5 and e4 pretty weak. } ) 11... Bg6 12. Nc3 Nf8 $1 { We keep the queen on b6 for now and bring the knight to e6 to attack the d4 pawn. } ( 12... Qd8 { is also possible. } ) 13. f4 { This looks very dangerous but it is not the end of the world. } ( 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Rd1 { This is pretty slow and leads to a positional game with equal chances. } 14... Ne6 15. Qd3 ( 15. Rb1 O-O 16. h4 Qc7 { We want to go ...Ng4 and ...f5-f4 on the kingside. } 17. Qd3 a5 $11 { Typical move to stop White's queenside expansion. } ) 15... O-O 16. a3 ( 16. b3 a5 $11 ) 16... a5 17. Rb1 Rfe8 $11 { We have a balanced position with ...Rad8 and ...Bf8 to follow next. } ) ( 13. Na4 Qc7 14. Nc5 N8d7 { We keep the knight on f6 rather than on f8. } ( 14... N6d7 { was played in the game 0-1 (41) Donchenko, A (2659) -Eljanov, P (2672) Tornelo INT 2021 which is also fine. } ) 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Nd3 ( 16. b4 { is met with } 16... a5 $11 ) 16... a5 $11 { It is useful to gain space on the queenside with a4 next. We will put our knight on b6 and castle kingside. } ) 13... Bc2 $1 { The bishop has a nice square on c2 and if the queen goes back to attack it, we get the e4 square. } 14. Qd2 { This is necessary here. } ( 14. f5 { is too reckless } 14... N8d7 15. g4 h6 $17 { Black was much better in the game 0-1 (63) Dzagnidze, N (2524) -Kosteniuk, A (2518) Chess.com INT 2021. } ) 14... Be4 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Nf5 Ne6 { The tables have turned here. White has to be careful not to get worse. } 18. Nxe7 Kxe7 19. f5 $1 { White gives up the d4 pawn to free up his pieces. } ( 19. e3 Rad8 $15 ) 19... Nxd4 20. Qg5+ Kf8 21. Be3 h6 22. Qh5 Kg8 $11 { Our king is more or less safe here as White does not have enough pieces to win on the kingside. The position still remains complex though with chances for both sides. } *

