1. b3 { The dreaded 1.b3 :) I think it is more of a meme online these days than people taking it seriously. There are multiple good systems to go for but we will keep our play similar to the lines we have seen so far. } 1... d5 2. Bb2 Bf5 { We get the bishop out of the pawn chain before we go for the move e6. However, unlike the lines we have seen so far we can get the bishop directly to f5. White has played very slowly with the move b3 and is not in a position to exploit our queenside. The lines with Qb3 are usually the critical ones. } 3. Nf3 { This can come via the Reti move order also. We just need to take care of ideas of Nh4. } ( 3. g3 { This will likely transpose to upcoming lines if we continue normally but we have the option to get control over the centre immediately. } 3... Nc6 $1 { This has been played in less than 10 games but is the best move in the position, preparing to go ...e5 next. } 4. Nf3 e5 $1 { We are ready to give up the e5 pawn to open up the position. The value of tempo is extremely high here. } 5. Bxe5 { White has to give up his important dark-squared bishop to win our pawn. } ( 5. Nxe5 Nxe5 6. Bxe5 d4 $1 { The dark-squared bishop is stuck now. } 7. Bg2 f6 8. Bf4 g5 $17 ) 5... Nxe5 6. Nxe5 h5 $1 { We are going after White's kingside now with ...h5-h4. } 7. Bg2 ( 7. Nf3 { allows us to go } 7... g5 $1 8. e3 Qf6 9. Nc3 O-O-O 10. h4 Bg4 11. Be2 gxh4 12. Nxh4 Nh6 $15 { White cannot castle kingside anymore and his king is stuck in the centre. We are going to open the centre with ...d4 next. } ) ( 7. h4 Qf6 8. d4 Bd6 9. Nf3 Nh6 { The knight is heading to g4 and we will castle queenside. } 10. Bg2 Qg6 { We are threatening both the c2 pawn and to take on g3. } 11. O-O Bxc2 $11 { We are on the better side of equality with the bishop pair. } ) 7... h4 8. d4 c6 9. Qd2 ( 9. O-O f6 $15 ) 9... Bd6 10. O-O f6 11. Nd3 Qd7 { We already have a big attack brewing up on the kingside with ...Bh3 coming up next. } 12. Nc3 Bh3 13. e4 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 hxg3 15. fxg3 Qh3+ 16. Kg1 Bxg3 $1 { We are winning a lot of pawns in return for the piece. The kingside is completely open now. } 17. hxg3 dxe4 18. Ne1 Qxg3+ 19. Ng2 f5 $36 ) ( 3. e3 { We will see the lines where White delays the move Nf3 here. } 3... e6 4. c4 ( 4. f4 { White plays in the style of the Bird and we are going to see this in the next chapter. } ) ( 4. g4 { White tries to go after our bishop on the kingside but it is a bit too drastic. } 4... Be4 5. Nf3 ( 5. f3 $2 Qh4+ $17 ) 5... h5 $1 { We immediately exploit the pawn on g4. } 6. d3 ( 6. gxh5 Rxh5 $15 { White's kingside is completely ruined for no reason. } ) 6... Bxf3 { We give up the bishop but ruin White's pawn structure and his kingside. } 7. Qxf3 hxg4 8. Qxg4 Nf6 9. Qg2 Nbd7 $15 { We will go ...g6 next followed by ... Bd6 and ...Qe7. The king will go to the queenside soon with a comfortable position. } ) 4... c6 { I like to keep our centre intact against these slow setups. We will just look to complete our development naturally. } 5. Nf3 Nd7 6. Nc3 Ngf6 7. Nh4 { This is the only try to stop us from achieving our ideal setup. } ( 7. Be2 h6 $11 { We get a very comfortable position now. We will continue with ...Bd6 and ...Qe7 followed by castling kingside. } ) 7... Bg4 8. Be2 { White exchanges the light-squared bishop which I feel is in in his favour. The pawn structure does not indicate that but our bishop was a monster on f5. } 8... Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. f4 { White wants to go ...g4 next on the kingside. } 11... Ne4 $1 { We kick the knight back and trade a pair of knights. } 12. Nf3 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Qe7 $11 { We can slowly prepare ...f6 and ...e5 in the centre. Black has no weakness in the position. } ) ( 3. d3 { This was recommended in Adhiban's course. He recognises the fact that it is very hard for White to get anything with the conventional systems. Instead, he tries to quickly get the move e4 in the centre. This leads to non-standard positions which may favour the better-prepared side. } 3... Nf6 4. Nd2 c5 { When given the chance we will try to get maximum space for our pieces. It is clear that White is not able to go c4 anymore as we will just go ...d4 blocking the bishop on b2. } 5. e4 { This is White's point. He gets e4 before we develop our pieces fully. It has been played only in 5 games so far. } ( 5. g3 { allows us to go } 5... Nc6 6. Bg2 e5 $11 ) ( 5. Ngf3 { This is pretty slow and does not fit in with White's approach. } 5... Nc6 6. g3 Qc7 $1 { We want to get our pawn to e5. } 7. Bg2 e5 8. e4 { This is the best try, fighting for the centre. } ( 8. O-O Be6 $11 { We get away from the move e4 and will now meet it with ...d4. The KID structure is not ideal for White with his bishop on b2. We have also not castled yet. } ) 8... dxe4 9. dxe4 Be6 { We are happy with the pawn on e4, blocking White's bishop on g2. We will jump in with the move ...Nd4 next. } 10. O-O Rd8 11. Qe2 Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 $11 { We will put our bishop on c5 next and castle kingside. } ) 5... dxe4 6. dxe4 Nxe4 7. Bd3 Nd6 8. Bxf5 ( 8. Qe2 { is not accurate. } 8... Nc6 9. O-O-O e6 $15 ) 8... Nxf5 9. Qf3 { White wants to castle queenside as soon as possible. } 9... Qc8 { We get the queen away from the 'c' file. We will get our knight to d4 next. } 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. O-O-O e6 12. Ne4 Qc7 $14 { We are likely going to give up a pawn on d4 next. I want to keep the option of directly developing the bishop to a3 here. } ( 12... Be7 13. g4 Nfd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 cxd4 16. Rxd4 O-O 17. Rhd1 Qc6 18. g5 Rfd8 ( 18... Rfc8 19. Qd3 $14 ) 19. h4 Rxd4 20. Rxd4 Rd8 21. Rxd8+ Bxd8 22. Kb2 { Adhiban ends here claiming that although the position is equal he prefers the combination Queen+Knight. It is objectively completely equal. } 22... Qd7 23. Qe3 b6 $11 ) ( 12... e5 $5 { This is an option to keep the game complex. You can check it out more if interested. } 13. Rhe1 ( 13. Kb1 Nfd4 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Qe2 Qe6 ) 13... Be7 14. g4 Nh4 ( 14... Nh6 15. g5 Nf5 16. Kb1 O-O 17. Nf6+ ) 15. Qg3 O-O 16. Bxe5 Nxe5 ( 16... Qe6 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nf4 Qe5 19. Nc3 Qg5 20. Ne4 ) 17. Qxe5 Nf3 18. Qxe7 Re8 19. Nf6+ gxf6 20. Qxf6 Qc6 21. Rd6 Qe4 22. Red1 Qxe2 23. R6d3 Ne1 24. Qg5+ Kh8 25. Qf6+ Kg8 $11 ) 13. g4 { White has to do something quick to show his compensation. } 13... Nfd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 cxd4 16. Rxd4 Ba3+ 17. Kb1 O-O { We get our king to safety. We will go ...Rfd8 next and trade one pair of rooks. White's king looks more exposed on the queenside. } 18. g5 Rfd8 19. Rhd1 Rxd4 20. Rxd4 Qe5 21. c3 Qxh2 $11 { Why not take the pawn? If White removes his rook from the 'd' file we can get our queen to his back rank. The position is dynamically balanced. } ) 3... e6 4. g3 ( 4. e3 Nf6 5. Be2 ( 5. Nh4 { can be met with } 5... Bg4 $11 ) ( 5. c4 c6 6. Be2 { With the bishop on e2, White is threatening to go Nh4 next. } 6... h6 7. O-O Nbd7 $11 { This is a comfortable situation for us with the bishop out of the pawn chain. } ) 5... h6 { Usually, the bishop going to e2 should be a reminder for us to go h6 and stop Nh4. } 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6 $11 { As usual, we have a very comfortable position in these structures. } ) ( 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 h6 6. g3 Be7 $11 { We we will continue as in the main line with ...0-0 followed by ...c6 and ...a5. } ) 4... h6 { It makes sense to stop Nh4 immediately here. I do not want to think about it each move. } 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. O-O Be7 { We put our bishop on e7 here as White is able to go d3 and e4 quickly in the centre. We do not want to worry about the move e5. Now, we can just ignore the threat. } 7. d3 O-O 8. Nbd2 ( 8. c4 { is always met with } 8... c6 $11 ) 8... c6 9. c4 { This is the more popular option as it does not block the bishop on g2. However, it is not clear what White intends to do next. } ( 9. Re1 { White goes for the e4 plan. } 9... Bh7 10. e4 a5 { This is a very common idea to go ...a4 on the queenside. White should not allow that. } 11. a3 { Now, he will meet ...a4 with b4 which is good for White. } 11... Nbd7 12. Qe2 ( 12. e5 Ne8 $11 { We will start playing on the queenside next. White has opened the diagonal for the light-squared bishop. } ) 12... Qb6 { We get the queen to the queenside now. I am struggling to see what White's plan is. } 13. h3 ( 13. Rab1 Qa6 14. e5 Ne8 $15 { Our typical plan here is to go ...a4 and after White goes b4, we break with ...c5. We want to open the queenside and target a3. } ) 13... Qa6 { We can take on e4 at any moment now and trade the queens. } 14. Kh2 Rfd8 $11 ) ( 9. Qe1 { I think this is just a worse version of Re1 as White ends up playing Qe2 next in most cases. } 9... Bh7 10. e4 a5 11. a3 ( 11. a4 { This is worse as it gives up the b4 square. } 11... Re8 12. Qe2 Nfd7 13. Ne1 Na6 $11 { We can go ...b5 next move. The knight can jump to b4 at any moment. Black is more comfortable. } ) 11... Nfd7 { We get the knight away from the kingside and can go ...Bf6 in the future. We will focus our play on the queenside. } 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Rfe1 Na6 14. h3 b5 $11 ) 9... Nbd7 10. Qc2 ( 10. Rc1 Re8 11. Rc2 { White wants to get his queen over to the a1, along the long diagonal. } 11... a5 12. a3 Bh7 13. Qa1 Bf8 14. Ne5 ( 14. Rfc1 c5 $15 { We want to go for the move ...d4 next and block the long diagonal. } ) 14... Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Nd7 16. Bc3 Nc5 $11 { The knight is heading to a6 and we can go ...b5 or ...c5 next. } ) 10... Bh7 11. a3 ( 11. Rac1 Re8 12. Qb1 { This is pretty slow and allows us to take control of the position. } 12... a5 13. a3 e5 $15 { We make use of the a3 pawn to get control over the centre. } ) 11... a5 12. Bc3 ( 12. e4 $6 { is rarely a good idea after having played the move c4. It weakens White's position with ...Nc5 coming up next. } 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. dxe4 Nc5 $15 ) ( 12. h3 Bd6 { We are ready to go for the move ...e5 next with a comfortable position. } ) ( 12. Rac1 Bd6 13. Qb1 Qe7 14. Qa1 e5 $15 { White is struggling against our strong central pawns. } ) 12... c5 $1 { We take the chance to prepare the move d4, gaining a tempo against the bishop on c3. In addition, we stop the move b4. } 13. cxd5 ( 13. e4 $6 d4 14. Bb2 g5 $15 { This is a very strong move, preparing to go ...next and kick the knight out. } ) ( 13. e3 a4 $11 { This is the reason why we went ...c5 to stop the move b4. } ) 13... exd5 14. e4 a4 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Bb2 b5 $11 { We have a great position on the queenside and the d3 pawn is a big target. Black feels more comfortable here. } *

