1. f4 { The Bird is a pretty aggressive but also dubious first move. Moving the 'f' pawn comes with the risk of weakening the king. Our play will be the same as in the lines we have seen so far. We will try to get the bishop out of the pawn chain before going ...e6. } 1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 { White will castle kingside next and try to get the move e4. He completely ignores the queenside. We have a few different ways of playing here. } ( 3. b3 { will transpose after } 3... Bf5 $11 ) ( 3. e3 Bf5 { This is not the most popular move but I value the consistency with our repertoire. } 4. b3 ( 4. d4 { The Stonewall structure is not great, especially when we have our bishop on f5. } 4... e6 5. Bd3 { White is forced to trade the light-squared bishop leaving him with a passive bishop on c1. } 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O $15 { [%csl Gf5] We will continue with the move ...c5 next with a better position. } ) ( 4. Be2 e6 5. O-O Be7 $11 { White will likely have to transpose to the lines with b3 next. } ) 4... e6 5. Bb2 Be7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O c5 { There is no need to be worried about Nh4. We will be happy to trade on f5 as it only helps us improve our pawn structure. The f3 knight is doing an important job, controlling e5. } 8. Ne5 ( 8. Nh4 Nc6 $15 ) ( 8. d3 Nc6 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. Bxe5 { Now, there is a real threat of White going g4 next. } 10... h6 11. Nd2 Nd7 12. Bb2 Rc8 $11 { We can regroup our knight to c6 via b8 next. Another plan is to trade the dark-squared bishops on f6. e4 can always be met with ...Bh7. We are on the better side of equality. } ) 8... h6 { It was important to get the h7 square for the bishop as White was ready to go g4. } 9. d3 Nfd7 10. Nxd7 ( 10. Nd2 { This only allows us to get a tempo by getting the knight to c6 to attack e5.. } 10... Nxe5 11. fxe5 $6 { This has been played the most but this structure is pretty bad for White with the bishop on b2. } 11... Bg5 12. Kf2 Nc6 $17 { We are ready to go ...d4 next. } ) 10... Qxd7 11. Nd2 Nc6 12. Qe1 f6 $15 { We have managed to blunt the bishop on b2. Next, we will start our play on the queenside with ... b5. } ) 3... g6 { I like this the best here as we keep the diagonal open for the light-squared bishop. The fianchetto works well here as White is not blocking the diagonal with d4. } ( 3... Bf5 { This fits in best with our repertoire but I think there are some slightly better options. It kind of falls into White's plan of going e4 in the centre. } ) 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 c5 7. c3 { This is the most common move here as White wants to prepare e4 slowly. He also has the plan of Na3-c2 now. } ( 7. Ne5 $5 { This is one of the top choices of the computer. White wants to get in the move e4 very quickly. However, it has not been played much. } 7... Qb6 { Our idea is to meet the central break with the move ... c4 and open up the position. This is a novelty in OTB chess. It has only been played in a couple of correspondence games. } 8. c4 ( 8. e4 c4+ 9. Kh1 cxd3 { The more files that get opened up, it becomes easier for us to go after White's centre. } 10. cxd3 dxe4 11. dxe4 Nc6 $15 ) 8... dxc4 9. Nxc4 Qc7 10. e4 Nc6 11. e5 Ng4 12. h3 Nh6 13. g4 f6 $11 { We will go ...Be6 next and get the took to d8. White's d3 pawn is a long-term weakness for him. He has to try and do something quick. } ) ( 7. Nc3 { White is preparing the move e4 but it is too provocative. } 7... d4 { We are happy to gain more space in the centre with a tempo. The knight lacks a good square on the board. } 8. Ne4 ( 8. Na4 Na6 9. c4 Rb8 { This is a typical move in these positions we want to ...b6 later. The rook was not well placed along the diagonal. } 10. Bd2 b6 11. Ne5 Bb7 $15 ) 8... Nxe4 9. dxe4 { White doubles his pawns in the centre, leaving us with a strong d4 pawn. } 9... Nc6 10. e3 Qb6 11. exd4 cxd4 12. Rf2 Rd8 $15 { We can continue with the move ... e5 next. If White goes e5 himself, we get the f5 square for the bishop. } ) ( 7. Qe1 { White is preparing to go for the move e4. } 7... Nc6 8. e4 { White takes the chance to go e4 before we stop it. We are well prepared to deal with it though. } ( 8. h3 { is too slow and allows us to go } 8... d4 $15 { [%cal Gf6d5] } ) 8... dxe4 9. dxe4 e5 $1 { This is a typical idea in these positions. We give up a pawn on e5 but will win it back very soon with ...Ng4 coming up. If not we want to eventually take on f4 and open up the position. } 10. Nc3 Nd4 11. Qd2 { White maintains the tension. } ( 11. fxe5 { is met with } 11... Ng4 $11 ) 11... exf4 12. gxf4 Be6 $15 { [%cal Gf6g4] We will get our knight to g4 next. White is the one lagging behind in development here and has a worse king. His only trump is the centre but there is not much that he can do with that here. } ) 7... Nc6 8. Na3 ( 8. Qe1 d4 $1 { We gain more space in the centre and discourage the move e4. We can either take on e3 or gain more space with ...e5. } 9. Na3 ( 9. e4 { can be met with } 9... e5 $17 ) 9... Rb8 { We want to go ...b5 and restrict the knight on a3. It also makes sense to get the rook away from the long diagonal. } 10. Nc4 dxc3 11. bxc3 b5 12. Nce5 Bb7 $15 { White has not been able to get the move e4 while we have made significant progress on the queenside. } ) ( 8. Qc2 d4 $1 { We saw this already in the previous line. We go ...d4 right when White is ready to go e4 } 9. Na3 ( 9. e4 dxe3 10. Bxe3 Bf5 $17 { The d3 pawn is gone as ...c4 is also a big threat here. } ) 9... Nd5 10. Bd2 Bg4 $1 { We are ready to give up the bishop on f3 to keep control over the e5 square. } 11. Rae1 ( 11. Nc4 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 b5 $15 { Now, the knight has no good square to go to. } ) 11... Rb8 { We will take on c3 the next move and go ...b5 on the queenside. } 12. Ng5 h6 13. Ne4 b6 $15 ) 8... Rb8 { We have seen this move several times already. We are preparing to go either ...b6 or ...b5 soon, so get the rook out of the diagonal. } 9. Ne5 { This is the most common move in the centre and White is ready to go e4 next. } ( 9. Nc2 b6 { We want to get the bishop to b7 and eventually prepare the ...e5 break. } 10. Bd2 ( 10. Qe1 Bb7 11. e4 { is met with } 11... dxe4 12. dxe4 Qd3 $15 { and White will lose the e4 pawn. } ) 10... Bb7 11. Re1 d4 { Once again, we are right in time before White goes for the move e4. } 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. Rc1 Nd5 $15 { The knight is well placed in the centre. We can go ...b5 and ...a5 on the queenside. White's pieces are cramped and lack space. } ) 9... Bf5 $1 { We stop the move e4 in time and also prepare to go ...Qc8 next to trade the bishops on h3. } 10. h3 { This is the best to stop the plan of ...Qc8. White can go g4 now. } ( 10. Nxc6 { This has been played in a few correspondence games but Black is just better after } 10... bxc6 11. Qe1 e5 $1 12. fxe5 Ng4 $15 { We will win the e5 pawn back with a big advantage. d4 does not help as we will go after it with .. .Qb6. } ) 10... Nxe5 { It is time to go after the pawn. } ( 10... h5 { is a decent option too. } ) 11. fxe5 Nd7 12. d4 cxd4 13. cxd4 Qb6 14. Kh2 Rbd8 { Next, we are planning to go ...Be4 and trade the light-squared bishops. } 15. Nb1 { White regroups his knight to get back into the game on c3. } 15... f6 16. Bxd5+ ( 16. Nc3 { can be met with } 16... e6 17. g4 Be4 18. Nxe4 dxe4 $36 { We will the pawn on e5 next and d4 is a big weakness. } ) 16... Be6 17. Bxe6+ Qxe6 18. exf6 Nxf6 $36 { We have a nice initiative here with the knight heading to e4 next. White is yet to finish his development with his pieces sleeping on the queenside. } *

